          "title": "Psalm 83 and the canon: a prayer the New Testament does not retract",
          "body": "Imprecatory psalms trouble modern readers, and Psalm 83 is among the most unrelenting. The canonical approach requires that the interpreter read it in full biblical context without softening its edge. Jesus quotes imprecatory material without apology (John 15:25 cites Psalm 35:19; 69:4). Paul deploys Psalm 69's imprecation in Romans 11:9-10 as prophetically fulfilled. The book of Revelation explicitly invokes the cry of the martyrs in terms reminiscent of the imprecatory psalms (Revelation 6:10). Reformed commentators Calvin and Spurgeon both insist that the imprecations are prayed not from personal vengeance but from zeal for God's covenant honor — a distinction the psalm itself makes by targeting 'Your enemies' and 'those who hate You' in 83:2. Keller observes that the imprecatory psalms guard against sentimentalizing God's justice — they insist that evil is not neutral, that God's silence is not indifference, and that His ultimate response to unrepentant hostility to His people is not silence but storm. The New Testament answer to Psalm 83 is not its cancellation but its fulfillment: Christ took the very judgment Asaph requests onto Himself on behalf of both Israel and the nations, so that the nations might seek the name of the LORD and know that He is Most High — which is precisely what 83:16-18 asks."
